<subSubSection id="5EFD94B6E1D76B4F26888FDF73080065" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" type="generic diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B4388C73BB6DBDD37F0850E5A7E3C903" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Generic diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C732B61DEAFA4E45C22052C79F902CE0" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
With a combination of typical abacetine characters such as clearly defined frontal impressions on the head; deeply impressed, linear basolateral pronotal impressions; no angular base of stria 1 on elytra; setose puncture at the base of elytral stria 2; well-developed elytral plica; metacoxal sulcus sinuate; abdominal ventrites without transverse sulci; ostium of aedeagus dorsal; and aedeagus left side dorsal in repose. Recognizable from other abacetine genera that share the character states listed above by the combination of deep post-ocular sulcus (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="20C1F841B4C65BAC3D3FC706D9715F4A" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Tiferonia leytensis sp. nov. head, left lateral view. Arrows indicate a post-ocular sulcus and b posterior edge of the orbit." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.906.48255.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/374830" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">1</figureCitation>
), smooth elytral margins, and lack of elytral discal setae.
</paragraph>
<caption id="EFC80F404FF62CD69470C822349A5FE1" doi="10.3897/zookeys.906.48255.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/374830" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
<paragraph id="DB062088D5FF4165B09D54A2EB476B3F" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis id="77DBA83384AFBA986A56EF69A14CFC62" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Figure 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4D686A7F3105C3D0FE2638C45AB54BBB" authorityName="Will" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tiferonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tiferonia leytensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leytensis">
<emphasis id="FB6C27FF8C910DD116F8BA1DEC3090B1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Tiferonia leytensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. head, left lateral view. Arrows indicate 
<emphasis id="AEFC9BE088D8E6BBD9FE045AE605512C" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">a</emphasis>
post-ocular sulcus and 
<emphasis id="41A09CB2815EEE3ED5DAD1531184723D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">b</emphasis>
posterior edge of the orbit.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9C4457043650EF3983F2485BC9777501" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" type="description">
<paragraph id="206C3EBB7FB701FA7EF0A85419CF66C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Genus characteristics.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B611613A566D72588B1EDB9672FC34C" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
Small size beetles (3.8-4.3 mm), castaneous or darker, nearly piceous colored, parallel sided, somewhat convex body form; apical segment of labial palpi elongate and fusiform. Mentum narrow triangular, shallowly emarginate; epilobes long and narrow, not prominent; median tooth prominent and entire, not reaching tips of lobes, mentum paramedial pits absent; paraglossae short, glabrous; submentum narrow, posteriorly sculpted; antennae of moderate length, somewhat thickly filiform, three basal segments glabrous except for apical ring of setae; postocular orbits moderately pronounced, with deep post-ocular sulcus (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="64D9C3257DBF0CBE696B1916A7BD3CE0" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Tiferonia leytensis sp. nov. head, left lateral view. Arrows indicate a post-ocular sulcus and b posterior edge of the orbit." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.906.48255.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/374830" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">1</figureCitation>
). Elytra free, lateral margin smooth; border entire across base; parascutellar stria present, joined to stria 1; 13-15 umbilicate setae in stria 8; hind wings fully developed; humeri obtusely angled with very small, usually sharp denticle; anterior tarsi of male with three basal segments narrowly dilated and squamose beneath. Aedeagus (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F918C2F9A432881136E1FF53B1DFCA0F" captionStart="Figures 2, 3" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 2, 3. Tiferonia species aedeagi, right lateral view (A) and dorsal view (B). 2 Tiferonia leytensis sp. nov. 3 Tiferonia parva." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.906.48255.figures2-3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/374831" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">2</figureCitation>
) with orifice on dorsum; parameres conchoid, the right smaller than the left.
</paragraph>
